{"key":"post-10801378","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10801378</id>\n<content>Use a tripod or book etc so the camera doesn't shake.&amp;nbsp; Turn off flash and use an external light beside the camera pointing at a 45 degree angle to your target.&amp;nbsp; This gives a realistic picture since there is both bright light and shadows present on the fruits.&amp;nbsp; On most digital cameras, you'll get a better pic by putting it about three to four feet away from the object and then zooming.&amp;nbsp; Don't forget to set the white balance.&amp;nbsp; Also, never use fluorescent and incandescent lights together.&amp;nbsp; Use one or the other and set the white balance accordingly.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10801441</next>\n<prev>10801228</prev>\n<first>10800881</first>\n<last>10811137</last>\n<when>1249440127</when>\n<utime>08/05/09 05:42 AM</utime>\n</post>"}